All these variations can be explained based on the degree of overlap between B-s and X-p orbitals. For instance, one can notice from Fig. 6 that the overlap in Sn-perovskite is more than that of Ge-perovskite and Pb-perovskite, suggesting that the band gap follows the order of CsSnI3<CsGeI3<CsPbI3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$CsSnI_{3}<CsGeI_{3}<CsPbI_{3}$$\end{document}. Based on this observation, it can be said that the greater ionic nature of hybridization between B-s and X-p orbitals results in blueshift of the band gap in halide perovskites. Further, the influence of compression on the lattice has been observed by the redshift of DOS with increasing pressure.

